Where do i start with? Minh the gentleman, His humble business or the whole package? As a resident of SW Bakersfield, I've always looked for people to repair iphones that are trustworthy.

I found the trustworthy, But never found the professional person in them "No disrespect", But when you approach Panda Fixx you see a professional small sign on the grass, Sign by the kitchen window "I love that idea" chairs, Fan and Small window for transactions.

I arrived and called the gentleman Minh, He was super welcoming from the begining, He said one moment i'll meet you by the window.

Very nice, Friendly and most importantly very knoledgeable in his field, Made me super comfy.

For some people a panda is a cute and cuddling animal, For the Asians especially chinese culture means health and well-being, I'd translate it that they respect people and wish them the best. So for this gentleman to serve our community with such hospitality and courtesy is what Bakersfield is all about. Good people, Great community, and we all help each other "Caring".

I'd say call, make an appointment online or even show up, He always welcome everybody at any time, But it's always good to give him a head sup just in case, Go there and have confidence that you'll be treated with care and respect.

IF you really looking to fix your Apple device with care, on the spot and no problems in the future PANDA FIXX is the business for you, Actually the business for everybody.

Thank you Minh for your help, i wish you the best in your business brother.

Bakersfield trust me, You gonna all thank me ;)<//text>

<Rate>5</Rate>< review>
The outdoor living section of Idler's Home in Paso Robles is outstanding for several reasons.  Its outdoor living manager, Donny Stiver, is a talented designer who is exceptionally familiar with a wide range of products for barbecue systems, spas, and even outdoor cabinets.  Donny takes the time necessary to understand his clients' tastes and expectations.   Prices at Idler's are very reasonable (but not cheap for good quality) and very competitive.  For more extensive outdoor projects, Donny provides assistance with design and personally checks on the installation.  The two other Idler's Home locations, San Luis Obispo and Santa Maria, have less extensive outdoor living displays, but rely upon Donny's expertise to help its local customers.< /review>

<Review>The two main appliances I have purchased at Idlers are, first my  Whirlpool fridge and then a Whirlpool oven/microwave.
Work had to be done in order for the oven to fit into the space required.
After oven was installed, I was annoyed that after oven was turned off, the fan continued to make a sound. My kitchen area and eating area are together. This fact should have been told by sales person. Also, it would have been a courtesy to inform me not to place anything on bottom of oven to catch spills as in earlier ovens one could do this. It is mentioned in the manual but in such small writing, it was missed. Another warning could have been to avoid too much broiling as when broiling a lamb chop the grease that spattered, also reached in between the double glass of the oven door and made long grease spills that could be seen from the outside.
As I had purchased a three year warranty and this grease spill happened after my initial warranty was over, I expected it could be taken care of.
I was told it was  "cosmetic". This is unacceptable and I consequently
got in touch with Rob, manager of repairs at Idlers. He was extremely courteous and understanding and, as a courtesy, agreed to have a service person come and clean the inside of the oven door. This  is something I cannot do myself as the oven door has first to be removed and then the two glass panes removed.
I really appreciate Rob helping me out.<//Review>< Pictures>

Ours is carpet flooring and you will get wooden flooring apt if needed. Maintenance service is very responsive and 99% of time my request gets done within 24hrs. The office staff and maintenance staff are very friendly and they will know you by your name. I would definitely recommend this community if you are family person and also if you are living with friends, it will give you homely  feeling around when you walk outside your apt. <review>Below: pros, cons, tips and details of my security deposit (not as scary as everyone says it is).

Pros:
- Leasing staff is very helpful, accommodating and nice. It's always a pleasure working with them or just talking to them (especially Jackie)
- Maintenance team is really nice and responsive. I really appreciate all of them.
- I like how the apartments look. I'm on the 2nd floor and the vaulted ceilings feels nice.
- Dedicated storage space on the patio
- Very close to downtown Sunnyvale
- Therefore pretty close to the Caltrain station too
- It's pet friendly.
- It's one of the best deals you can get quality/price wise
- The laundry facilities are always clean
- Despite how dirty some people living here can be, the maintenance team always makes sure to clean the common areas and the outside feels nice
- They waved the cleaning fees ($60) when we moved out (because I asked for them to do it as they promised when we moved in - the cleaning hasn‚Äôt been done properly and it wasn‚Äôt really clean)

Cons:
- It's SO loud. Neighbors let their kids scream like crazy all the time.
- Overall, the worst part are SOME of the neighbors (others are great). They leave lots of dirty stuff on their patios / front doors. Some even left food for days in front of their doors! And then they're surprised to see cockroaches visit them...
- When we moved in, the cleaning hasn't been done properly. It felt a gross unfortunately .
- Doesn't have AC nor in unit laundry
- I felt like they charged a bit too much when we left. Pictures that I‚Äôve put here are from when we left (was cleaner than when we moved in IMO)

Here is what they charged:
- 1x1 touch up paint: $129.17 (really?)
- 1x1 carpet clean (I cleaned them all)
- Cleaning: $60 (I called and they reimbursed me)
- 4 drip pans: $20 (that‚Äôs completely normal and I have nothing to say regarding that)
Utilities: $162.21
Total: $461.38

The reason why despite these cons I'm giving 4 stars is because we overall really liked our place and we loved the staff.

Also, I would recommend getting a corner unit. Otherwise the second window you will have in your living room (the one closest to the kitchen) won't open and you will have way less light.</review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMIR2bdPiNJ9hxNpafZdVrJqfkhuWqyIj0MhRxI=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM4RPeD9MkYKal-WiXoCGFvoPaoDO0uF05URg76=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPymqi-gvg5_l5ugG9gFOsBHRJW5P5Lzj0BKVZG=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPkV3wlEIVtlwsGPewWwTb3inobxodpVEblunjx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNNyp3Uet_CnPB_WLQfiGmiBWatsd-q1Y5H-Vfh=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO0-WBz8zzcj6C8efKeQsA30a7rx_quKjh1tTmB=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPQxj6XpAhahhSqjxnA4tobv1oQuokyxXnPmL0I=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN-rRiSIwwafbzbyDNI0wsFSJZEprPK7KtoPXpP=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP8zOgSOjGxLDFPIu6QiXZi5DIKmIRYy956WSmt=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPW-Y0zk2Ee7EBNF8XFIEKf6Gi-qPFsjd9lbjsF=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMUurC5s20otFUgiW6Q7ysrcUQykV74jY-t55to=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMhhc7C7oT3Q4qsjr6oFWSXgz7AAqKAFG4CTKkM=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pics>< Resp>

Place:
Very nice and cozy place to live in. 13 min walk to CalTrain, Target, and Wholefood and close to a lot of great restaurants.  Across the street from three bus routes (20-21-56) and work shuttles. Very family friendly community and very safe.

Management:
Always been helpful and easy to communicate with all the time. They Emailed us when ever there is any construction, safety concerns, and even address noise complains fairly. They made it easy to move in and out. Their moveout charges been discussed ahead of time and even gave us options on what they expect and what they can offer. Honestly, their move out charges are fair. We had two pets but we kept our routine cleaning and vacuuming and we didn't see these crazy charges everyone is talking about.

**A special thanks for Jackie for handling everything since the move in, addressing any questions or concerns during the stay, and making the move out process simple. You are one of a kind. **

Maintenance:
Very professional, on time, and get things done the right way. They were amazing specially during the pandemic, they practiced all precautions when they visited. Laundry rooms are clean and kept maintained, public areas are spotless clean and maintained, even the roof of the parking spot is cleaned and maintained. It's that attention for details that makes it look perfect.< /Review>

< text>
I would stay away from this place if your looking for an honest mechanic. The owner Walter does make a list of all the services your car needs but he either doesn't know what he is talking about or he is just trying to get you to do unnecessary services. My car was perfectly healthy and I just wanted him to do a pre purchase inspection. He said my car needed a timing belt at 80,000 and when I told him that the dealer recommends changing it at 120,000 for my car he just made an excuse about how he has to check it and never mentioned anything about that again. Had I not known that he probably would convince me to change the timing belt. He also said that my car needs $3000 engine work because it was leaking coolant. After putting the car on the jack and seeing that there was no coolant leaking he said that it leaks at night, if that was true I would have to either add coolant or the engine would over heat and I don't add coolant and its always full like its supposed to be.  And just to confirm that my car didn't have a coolant leak I took it to a AAA certified mechanic who clearly stated that the engine had no issues or leaks. I am sure if he is doing this with me then he will do it to everyone else who walks into his shop. There are plenty of good mechanics out there so you don't need to come here. <Name>Jay Dorman</Name><date>1366259495503<//date><rate>5< /rate>< text>
I can absolutely recommend Right Solution without reservation.

I just bought a 2011 Saab 9-3 convertible, and wanted to get the oil changed, have it checked out, etc.  I tried Ed Little and Cal, but neither one works on Saabs.  However, Ed Little's recommended Right Solution.  Which is noteworthy in and of itself.

ANYway, I brought it in right when they opened (at 8am on a Wed).  Walter jumped in the car with me, and took it for a test drive.  Really appreciate that he did that.  So we got back, and he had his guys go over the car for an hour with a proverbial fine tooth comb.  When they were done, they brought me into the garage and gave me a bit of a technical tour of the car, which was great!  Then Walter told me it was perfect...not a single thing wrong.  Asked me to bring it back in 5k miles for an oil change and in 6k to have the break pads checked.  I totally expected to have the oil changed because the selling dealer said it might need it.

When I asked Walter what I owed him for the time, he said 'nothing.'   As in nada.  Zip.  Zero.  Zilch.  I even insisted on paying for the hour of his tech's time.  He was adamant that I pay nothing.  Said that the check up was free.  He just asked me to tell my friends about his shop.  Which I will!

He could have changed my oil, replaced the break pads, and charged me $100 for the hour of time.  I would have paid $400 without even thinking about it.  Instead, Walter took the high road.  I'm beyond impressed.

You know what else I noticed?  He really respects his technicians.  Treats them like friends.  Maybe that seems random and irrelevant, but I think it speaks to his integrity.

I actually found an honest mechanic.  So, so relieved.</text>

< Review>
Don't let them near your RV.

Sorry I called them.  I scheduled to leave on a dry camping trip and I wasn't sure about my house batteries so I searched the Web for batteries.  I found Right Solutions Inc. who was more than willing to come to my home and install 4 new batteries.  The first mistake I made other than using their services, was assuming the installer new what he was doing and could connect everything the way it was.  When he finished I checked the charge on my monitor and found that the batteries weren't fully charged.  I was informed that these were new batteries and just needed to charge overnight, so I connected my battery charger and charged the batteries over night.  They were charged the next morning and as I left for my vacation I was confident that I wouldn't have a battery problem but I was wrong.  The next morning my batteries were completely dead and I had to use my generator which should have recharged my batteries through the inverter, but they didn't charge.  I called the warranty number on the battries and they sent me to the nearest dealer who checked the batteries and said they were good but could have been installed wrong. This was out of their expertise.  To make a long story short, since I left my battery charger at home I ended up purchacing a new on at WalMart in Arizona to charge my batteries. I finnaly had a mechanic look at my batteries and it was determined that the insaller connected a wire from the inverter to the negative side instead of the positive.  He corrected it and the system started charging. When I returned home I contacted Right Solutions requesting some type of compensation for the money I spent and was told that their installer experienced and would not have done anything wrong however, we all make mistakes.  They refused to compensate me for the extra money I spent instead they want to have their electrician look at my RV and see if there is a problem.  Of course there's no problem now I paid to have it fixed.  I will continue to try to resolve this issue but it doesn't look hopeful.  I thought I was saving money but it ended up costing me more.  Next time I will buy from Interstate.

I received a call from Rudy the owner of Right Solutions who informed me that he didn't know about the problem I had with the batter installation. It seems that the supervisor talked to me. Anyway the problem has been resolved and I was compensated for the money I spent while in Arizona.  It seems that Right Solutions is interested in providing good customer service by standing behind their work.  That's all I wanted.<//Review>

<Text>We had family come up from L.A. and doing the escape rooms at the Code Zone in Petaluma were perfect for some great family bonding. The wonderful family who run the place were very nice and patient in accommodating our group of 14. We split into 2 groups, 1 group of adults and the other group made up of the kids. Code Zone was able to run both themed rooms concurrently so both of our groups could perform the rooms in the same 1 hour block.

Our plan was for the adults to do "X Marks The Spot" and the kids to do "Get To The Game." Both of our groups were able to beat our rooms and had so much fun doing so, we decided to book the next hour so we could swap rooms! Again, the adults were able to finish our room, while the kids came really close to finishing theirs. Super fun!

Completing the rooms was accomplished by dividing up tasks, with communication being the absolute key! If you see something, say something, because someone in your group may have come across something that may have you stumped. Overall, the rooms were really fun with the degree of difficulty of each being pretty comparable to one another.

I definitely would recommend Code Zone for a family group event or any other group setting for that matter, whether it be for a work team building excercise or just a group of friends getting together looking for some good fun! Thanks Code Zone! We had a blast!<//Text>< Response>

We werent sure about going during Covid19 but saw reviews about their sanitary practices that reinsured us.

When we got there and did the pirate escape room, our takeaways are:
1. it was very sanitary and everything was wiped down, hand sanitizer available, masks worn and you only do the room with your group.
2. it was fun for the whole family.  we were four  people including our 12 and 10 year old daughters.  We were on the last clue when time ran out and for all four of us it was fun and challenging and time flew.
3. The staff are the owners and inventors of the eacape rooms and are super nice and really get into seeing how folks in the escape room are doing.  afterwards they said when they traveled (before covid) they always do escape rooms where they go because they love seeing different escape rooms.  they also shared with great enthusiasm how they found the different pictures or props that make up the escape room.

Definitely check out Code Zone Petaluma.  It was a great activity for the family.<//text>

I hate them. I did not need the lift. He knew I would just agree to it considering iv'e never had it done before and knew nothing about botox :(   being a Dr he should have known by looking at me that I wouldn't of needed it, or at least informed me that my arch would go away!  but again, because I was a new patient and never had it done before, I would just agree to it all.. then the lip fillers was ok, however, I paid a total of $1414.00 and did not even get the small laugh lines filled. < Text>
First time attending any Disney themed park (I'm in my 30s). I expected a lot of walking but I did not anticipate all of the people, especially on a Thursday. My favorite ride hands down was Incredicoaster. I was able to ride 3 times, and thankfully, the wait times were never as long as advertised. My only disappointment was at the very end of the night. We were actually on the coaster and saw that a car was going to run again with only two rows filled. We asked (very nicely) if we could ride along with the last group since it was partially empty, but the attendant just pointed to the exit. I get that everyone has had a long day, but a bit of friendliness and an actual response wouldn't have taken much out of her. Also, by mid-afternoon, the bathrooms smelled HORRID. Other than that, wonderful day at the park.</Text>

Rather depressing to see the state the store is in these days. Used to be crowded at all hours with a great selection of everything.

Last few times I've gone the selection has become less and less, they seem to be cutting back on the employee hours quite a bit as well, as it was a nightmare to find anyone able to provide assistance.

The associates I was able to track down were extremely helpful and knowledgeable, and basically bent over backwards to help me find the cables I was looking for.

Still a great store, just feels like its slowly getting phased out by its competitors.<//Text>

< Text>
Fry's used to be a good place to get electronics, like computers and digital cameras, DVDs and music. Then, in a misguided attempt to be all things to all people, they expanded too fast into large appliances, furniture, and other hard goods. Music and movies, not so much. This Holiday season, the store is VERY poorly stocked, with very little merchandise to sell. One almost thinks they are going to close the store, they just haven't said so yet.</Text>

<rate>5< /rate>< username>
Matt G<//username>
< pics>
None<//pics>
<resp>None< /resp>< Text>
I give Fry's a 5 star not for how it is today, but how it once was.

I remember when I first moved to California and saw a Fry's for the first time. The massive Jacobs ladder running, the Cafe was bustling, the Deep see diver tanks lively and epic with the wall waterfalls, and the fish tanks full of such exotic looking fish and even a shark at one point. An electronic store that had so much, everything you could ever think of or want.

Their computer repair service was awesome, and they would hold classes to help teach you how to build your own PC. The staff were intuitive, knowledgeable and caring. And again, you could find EVERYTHING. Are you gamer? Upgrade your rig, get a new game, Mt. Dew and snack aisle right there for binge gaming. Need a fridge? Done. Are you a baker? Bam every kitchen appliance from overs, to mixing bowls to espresso machines. Everything.

This store was so phenomenal and was a great introduction to this franchise and the state of Cali as well. It had easily become my favorite location and my wife and I met so many great employees here.

Sadly the store has become a husk of itself. I have seen this so many times and its heart breaking to see so many shelves empty or removed. Fewer employees than ever and most seem to know an end is near even if they wont voice it. Their actions speak all. The fact that the Register numbers in the back row of the check out counter and all but 10 of the register computers are gone says they wont make it to the holiday season and they know it.

I have read all over that its not just this one but all Fry's locations are going through this. Its a classic sign of the end of a great franchise. I will miss them so when they are finally gone, and am waiting for an official announcement, but until then I will continue to try to support my favorite store until alas their doors close once and for all.</Text>

This used to be one of my favorite stores,  until they changed their model and now it's a ghost town.  Zero selection of anything and mostly empty shelves.  I came back twice in the last few months to see if they had solved their problem.  But no... and worse yet, the staff could care less.  I asked the only one employee I saw walking around if he had heard of any new updates on the store going back to normal and he laughed and said it looks fine to me'.   On the way out I said to the security guy that sits by the door and checks receipts, that it's depressing. This place has a weird vibe, like it should be a casino or something. There's a cafe in the middle of the store, and there's an office/gaming chair farm. Genuinely feels like an aesthetic distopia. There's are fish tanks and fountains with water running upwards!

<review>HUGE store! They carry just about anything that plugs in, and many things that don't, like office furniture, games, and exercise equipment. Unlike other brick and mortar stores these days, Fry's also has a decent selection of small components and accessories for building computers, gaming systems, and fixing electronics. They also price match, including online. There is one major downside however...many of the employees think they are knowledgeable and electronics savvy, but many of them are not. I strongly recommend that you research what you need before you go, or better yet, bring someone who is knowledgeable with you. Any time I have asked for help simply locating a specific product in the store, the employee has tried to talk me into getting something else that wasn't going to solve my issue. Very annoying and a waste of time. As for major electronics, like laptops, computers, phones, and such, we'll stick with Costco. That said, we probably pop over once a month for something we couldn't find elsewhere.<//review><UserId.>101308329568846894611< /UserId.><Date>1529341864615<//Date><resp>None< /resp><user_name>B E</user_name><rate>4<//rate><Pictures>None<//Pictures></record></dataset><record>

<userid>108636396478416425449</userid><date>1554127849440< /date><resp>None</resp>< Name>
Eric Acosta<//Name>
<rate>4<//rate>< Text>
As far as electronics goes, they have mostly everything I need. Even if I don't purchase anything during my visits, I can personally see the quality, options, and accessories a piece of equipment may come with. It sure beats the hassle of buying something online, being disappointed, then having to return the product and having to do it all over again. Big box stores still have a place in our society and Fry's is an example of this.

This location is normally pretty quiet and clean but be aware of open products. It seams that people like to open sealed packages to check the contents. But rather than purchasing the package they opened, they tend to put that one back and purchase another unopened item.

Black Friday here is insane but I learned that if your not one to wait in line for the door Buster's, they may still have the product you want if you stroll in during regular store hours. This all depends on the product you are looking for so don't try this for an item that is highly sought out for.

Make sure you sign up for their promo codes too. This can and will save you a lot of money when purchasing certain items. Once signed up just keep an eye on your email, some items are only discounted for single days and are usually in limited quantity.<//Text>

<Rate>3</Rate>< Review>
What used to be the best place to get anything for my computer has become just somewhere to go when you don't want to wait a day or two for Amazon. They have a decent selection for most items you need, but can be lacking in other areas. Stay away from any open box items, when an item is returned they usually just throw a sticker on it for a small amount off and put it back on the shelf. The shakes and sandwiches in the Cafe are good. The prices are usually comparable and be sure to search up the price online as they do price match internet prices, but they will be picky about the source.< /Review>

< Review>
Really sad what happened to Fry's... This used to be a place you could spend hours, it was very exciting to shop there. I went last week, hearing they are closing, thinking I would find deals but the store seemed to be in "suspended liquidation." Most shelves were empty with all popular items gone, what remained was not discounted at all, and what was left were only the items that got bad reviews or were overpriced or obsolete. Some small items I took to the register rang up for more than what was posted on the shelf and they wouldn't adjust it. Only giving them 2 stars because I had so many good experiences there over the past 20 years. Save yourself the time, its not worth visiting Fry's anymore.< /Review>

< review>
Great customer service in the store. Employees are nice and usually know what they are talking about. They don't try and pressure you into buying anything. Overall the store is awesome and the employees make for a great experience in person.

The customer service over the phone is less then adequate, expect 20min wait times before an employee will answer who will then transfer you and you will have to wait again. I've called 5 times in the past 2 days wasting a couple hours on the phone, the first time i got connected with a guy who had no idea what he was talking about and gave me some bogus info, he said if it didn't work I'd have to come in to the store, it didn't work. I simply needed to be connected to a sales manager who assured me he would send me some promotion codes for buying a new graphics card.

The next two times i called after a 30 min wait time nobody was answering in the department so the customer service put in a ticket with my information and told me i would be contacted shortly, which never happened.

I called again and finally got connected to the right department but the manager wasn't there.  An employee took my info and told me he had no idea when I might get my promo codes. The only reason i chose FRY's was because they offered the codes.

Currently I'm still calling for the codes and have had no luck, I wouldn't bother usually but its over a 100 bucks in video games I'd be missing out on.

Finally emailed the store manager with the details and had my promotional codes within a couple hours.</review>

1565469927827</time>
<rating>1< /rating>< review>
I used to love going to Fry's. It was always a fun experience checking out the giant fishtanks and browsing the vast inventory. I could always find some obscure movie or CD and enjoy people watching with crowds on Saturday afternoon. That was four years ago.
I went back today to show my 10 year old what an awesome place Fry's was and browse the CDs and DVDs . We were completely disappointed. Not only did they have virtually no CDs or DVDs, half the shelves in the entire store were empty. On a Saturday afternoon there was one register out of twenty open and maybe a dozen customers in the store. How they are still in business like this is beyond my understanding. I don't expect it to remain around much longer. I have no reason to ever go there again. It's a shame.< /review>

<name>Joe Bruening<//name><time>1543845412536<//time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>
< Review>
We don't have a Fry's where I'm from and I used to frequent radio shack. I was looking for some electronics components to fix my microwave and my buddy said just go to Fry's. I of course had no idea what he was talking about, but decided I'd go anyways. I walked in there with the intention of buying two or three small components and I walked out with over $300 dollars of gear. This store is the coolest store I've ever been in. Some of the prices can be a bit high but they will have sales that are unbelievable. If you are looking for almost anything technology related chances are they'll have it. Are you trying to build your first pc? They're employee's in that department are pretty knowledgeable and will help you find the best bang for your buck. I would recommend this store to anyone who asks about it. 10/10 will shop at again.</Review>

<userid>102153046854669855182<//userid><Name>Jack Martinez<//Name><Date>1516767397344< /Date>< Rating>
3<//Rating>
< text>
Short version -

Great if you're looking for something specific and don't care about the price. Usually has the latest and greatest tech. Certain departments need to be more knowledgeable about their products.

Positives

-Expansive inventory
-Niche PC hardware not carried by other big box stores
-Friendly staff

Negatives

-None competitive pricing
-Old inventory that isn't discounted
-store organization can be lacking

I have had positive, negative, and overall neutral experiences here. In most cases the staff is friendly, but usually uninformed. Staff in the PC gaming department could use some polishing on the latest tech and what is available. On the other hand I have had amazing experiences in the TV department. The store has such a wide variety of items that I can usually find what in looking for or find something I didn't intend on getting. Unfortunately, they are usually not the lowest price wise and that gap is not filled by quality of service. This can also be seen by the items they have in stock. For instance I have seen Razer PC gaming gear that isn't even being made anymore, at prices at the same level as the latest and greatest hardware. I have also had negative experiences here with customer management and store organization. I have seen the San Marcos store in complete disarray before. There was a point where I went to buy a new PC gaming chair and test out the various models they have, but every single one was just being lounged in by out of control kids and various people just screwing around in the chairs.

Not a bad place, but definitely doesn't stand out as my one stop shop.<//text>

< rate>

< text>
I'm copying this from my Yelp, as it's extensive. Fry's has frustrated me enough, and wasted enough of my time, for me to create and leave a review here:

My experience with the San Marcos store started after black Friday this past year. My husband went to pick up a 60" TV your store had advertised on sale for $500. He went in the morning and bought the TV, to be picked up later that day by both of us, since we lived on the third floor of our apartments at the time. When we returned later that afternoon to pick up our TV, the personnel at the door told us the TV had been paid for and taken, not paid for--to be picked up, like my husband had explicitly requested. They had given him the wrong receipt and while we waited for the management to figure out what they did wrong, we saw his TV in the "waiting to be picked up" portion of the store. With his name on it. The cashier who had made the mistake, never told anyone, so the man who was trying to figure things out looked at us like we were there trying to steal a free TV the entire time, while we were just there trying to pick up our TV and go home.

It took them over an HOUR to rectify this situation, during which we didn't get an explanation, and after which, we didn't even get a simple apology. We wouldn't have even had an explanation if my indignation didn't lead to my requesting to see the manager. The manager helped little, I told him as much, and that his personnel needed training on 1) communication, and 2) customer service. Frustrated, I walked out. When I returned 10 minutes later to pick up the TV with my husband. As we proceeded to walk out the door, after getting our receipt checked by a different person, the original guy runs up behind us and tells us to stop, stop. Now we were being unequivocally treated as thieves, as I can only assume they were discriminating against us because no one else was being treated this way.

I am familiar with discrimination, growing up as a minority. My husband was not, growing up in a heavily Mexican community. This experience deeply hurt him.

After our latest visit to the Fry's store in San Diego (another review), the continual lack of communication, terrible customer service, and training, linked with the discrimination my husband experienced at this store, has cemented that this chain is not worthwhile.< /text>

< Review>
Today I traveled to Fry's in San Marcos located roughly 40 miles from my house. I spent over an hour and a half in the store picking out parts for a new PC build, having trouble with in stock items and what not, but understandably that is to be expected especially around this time of year.
After sitting in traffic for well over I was excited to put together my Ryzen 5 1600, among other items. The CPU, apparently the only one of its model they had in stock, was an open box item, which is totally fine as long as it is functional and looks good. Upon opening the box at home I noticed that the CPU was definitely used, and although Fry's notate that they inspect the product before re-selling; the product was covered in residue , missing instructions, and most importantly missing thermal paste. At this point I was tempted to just get some thermal paste from my local Best Buy and be done with it, however, I decided to call Fry's and see if they had any more Ryzen 5 1600's in stock. Prior to heading out another 40 miles to the store I was assured by the employee on the phone that my product was in stock.
I arrived at Fry‚Äôs 40 minutes before closing and was informed that my CPU was not actually in stock, or at the very least the employees could not locate it. In an attempt to resolve the situation I asked if Fry‚Äôs could either ship a CPU to my house so I would not have to travel another 80 mile round trip or compensate me with thermal paste from the store. Both of my suggestions were rudely denied by the supervisor- even more insulting was the fact that they wanted me to pay for additional thermal paste (the thermal paste that should have been included with my product). After discussing the situation with several other employees they tried to explain to me that because I price-matched the CPU with another retailer they couldn't provide me a tube of thermal paste from their shelves, which makes no sense to me at all. It may seem a little ridiculous that I didn't just give up and buy thermal paste myself, however, the principle of the matter was that it was something that was intended to be included with the product I paid for.
Through a lot incompetency and frankly ridiculous policy, Fry‚Äôs managed to consume about 6 hours of my day and tried to tell me that If i didn't utilize their price matching policy they would have conceded. So, for the price of a $3 tube of thermal paste Fry‚Äôs lost a long time customer and seeing all the other recent reviews I am assuming that I am not the only one.<//Review>

Saturday the day AFTER Black Friday I went to Fry's. A man in the check out line was commenting tohis wife as we walked by that 2 1/2 hours in line was crazy and they still had 15-20 people ahead of them. <gmap_id>0x80dc755aa2b28be1:0x51e22e4c135aeec9<//gmap_id><rating>5< /rating>< Text>
I see a lot of negative reviews here so I though I would write something a little more positive.  I have purchased 3 computers at Fry's over the years and have never had a problem.  The last computer was a Lenovo Z710 with 1TB hard drive and 16GB memory which listed for $1599 I found a bargain online for $999.00 and went to Fry's to see if they had it and would match the price.  The had it and they had it on sale for $1350., however they matched the price even though I felt they would rather not.  No hassles.  I have purchased many items from them including a 55" Sony TV which was a current model that I bought for 1/2 the list price on sale.   I have never had a defective product.  I did return an item than I bought by mistake and returned it without any hassle.  I shop at the store in San Marcos, find it clean and well stocked.  Maybe I'm lucky, which I'm not, but find Fry's to be a great place to buy electronics.< /Text>

< Review>
This place is huge, well decorated inside (underwater theme with beautiful fish tanks) and has all the home electronics you could want, plus a bunch of other eclectic items. The staff is typically meh, but have been getting better over the last year or so.
Their pricing is weird, some things have really good prices, but most are a bit high, so you really need to double-check before you buy there.
Last, I HATE the 1000 foot maze they make you walk through to get to a register. Several years ago, they needed that line space, but in the last few years (even during the weeks between Thanksgiving and Christmas or other big sales holidays) there have only been a few people in line in front of me. They recently took out half of the 50+ registers to make more counter room. I am guessing that they will be going out of business in the next year or so at this rate.</Review>

3< /Rating>

<review>Of the two Frys in San Diego county, this is the nice one.  This one was originally built as a Frys whereas the one in Mission Valley was converted.   As such, the decor in the San Marco's has a theme (Atlantis).

Frys is the best place to go to look at and touch real goods rather than the internet and they will match any price you pull up on your phone. < review>
As a local Depot, they have a lot of selection, however; they're always out of stock on any deal they present and they always find a reason why they don't price match. Oh, yes, no rain checks on sold out deals either. Funny, their deals are, again, always sold out.

They can't compete with Amazon, Newegg, or Microcenter. You're honestly better off spending your money else where and waiting a couple days to get your merchandise.

My 8700k combo with ram was $800 at frys, and $580 at Microcenter, of course frys wouldn't bend.

Of the home stereo equipment that sell, it's so over priced, you're honestly better off dealing with one of the competitors they supposedly price match but always find a reason not to. When it comes down to it, take your business elsewhere.</review>

< Review>
The worst experience of my life. I bought two laptops for work for over 500 dollars each from a sales rep and manager named Qi. Less than two months later the laptops hard drives start making a loud grinding noise and  Frys own tech support informs me both hard drives have gone bad and is very noticeable due to the light being on and the horrendous sounds the hard drive was making. Tech support was very friendly and knowledgeable and the best part about frys. When I went to customer service for an exchange customer service rep named Mayra was unfriendly, unwelcoming and even annoyed that we needed her help. She was even amused as she knew they were not going to help us in anyway. Then the same person who sold me the laptops named Qi said they could not exchange it or refund and tech support can not fix it. So basically I'm out over 1000 dollars and the manager above Qi did not even have the decency to talk to me face to face. I can't believe they are selling these overpriced laptops that break down and offer no help. I would give zero stars if I could and I advise everyone to go get your electronics and Best Buy or any other place that will actually take care of you. Please buyers beware.<//Review>

<Rate>1</Rate>< text>
Probably final review: The shelves really are nearly, or actually empty now. Really sad to see the chain go, but apparently all Fry's are like this. Best Buy is a bit of a joke. I guess all we have left is the Microcenter in Tustin to be the entire state's one good computer component store? Holy cow.

New review: It's a sad day for me indeed, but my once five star rating is now a one star. Since December this location has not replenished it's stock at all. Most of the shelves are FILLED with either large boxes they used to keep in the warehouse area, or with very cheap products that I assume other Fry's locations couldn't sell. It leaves me to speculate, either they are preparing for a big remodel and didn't want to fill up on stock, or what I think is more likely: this location is probably preparing to go out of business. They selection has become such a joke otherwise. Items advertised they not only are out of, but haven't had at this location since November. There is barely anything to browse anymore, they're just missing so much product. It's a really sad state, and downright frustrating to try to find stuff you need here now. If they get their stock back, I'll put my rating back to 5 stars. But at this moment, this doesn't even feel like a Fry's anymore.

Original review: I don't know why so many people are complaining about the service here. Most electronics stores I go to, the staff has no idea what I'm talking about. At Fry's about half the staff actually knows what they're talking about, and honestly that is impressive.
Selection is really good, and among all the Fry's electronics I've been (six of them) this is probably the largest/easiest to navigate.

I know some people prefer the employee going to you, but I hate being asked by every employee at Best Buy if I need help. I don't want to answer the same question every ten seconds. I would much rather go to the employee once I figure out what my question IS. And this is what you can do at Fry's.

To reiterate: If you NEED HELP just go ask them! I don't see why everyone reviewing this fry's seems to want some employee to just follow them through the store. That sounds more annoying, especially when if you bother to ask them a question, they are very friendly!<//text>

<rate>3</rate><Review>I have known and loved Frys for years. Shopped there when they were mostly components to build your own projects or computers.
First NEVER buy returns or opened box items. Having done this and gotten a bad device more than once I will never do it again. Someone probably bought it and either didn't like it, broke it or found it didn't work right, the item was returned, put back in the box, and back on the shelf. They do not inspect returns.
Second They have a big selection more than almost any others
Third Price matching is spotty. I have gotten price matches but I didn't get a match on a Samsung 32GB SDRAM because the online model had an A at the end. The package was identical etc.but still no match.
Fourth employees are not specially trained so don't expect to get difficult questions answered. They know about as much (or a slightly less) than employees in any dept. store.
Fifth  it is one of the few places where you can still walk in and buy components. That won't matter to many but it makes a difference to some of us when we need one more chip, transistor or cap.
So I consider Frys a mixed bag. But still go in once a week.< /Review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Response>

<Text>Some of the staff at Frys know there stuff, others are dumber then mud fences. I bought a computer from the sales man and unboxed and set it up. Found out the guy sold me the wrong computer (desktop didn't have built in WIFI). So I went back a little upset and asked to return the item. Got a knowledgeable sales man and asked to upgrade my 799.99$ computer to a really nice 1499.99$ gaming computer. We look on the internet and find an awesome deal for 1399.99$ no tax. Sales guy says lets do it, I'm going to get my manager. Manger Fabian Toledo comes over and says no he can't do it. But he can do 1250.00 and I pay taxes. Roughly 1360.00$ after taxes. Im like deal. Fabian then says wait. (Guy has no idea how to do math) I made a mistake. I say okay, lets just honor the 1399.99$ price match. He fights with me for 45min over 32$. In the end Fabian Toledo was rude and called me"dog" (guess he thinks we live in the hood) and never honored my price match.

MORAL of the story: NEVER DEAL WITH FABIAN TOLEDO!!! He's rude, angered, and has not passed 3rd grade mathematics. Feel sorry for someone that loses a 1400.00$ sale over 31-32 dollars.<//Text>< Rate>
